1
00:00:19,917 --> 00:00:21,917
[water trickling]

2
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:24,000
[seagulls squawking]

3
00:00:24,083 --> 00:00:26,083
[waves crashing]

4
00:00:44,917 --> 00:00:46,917
["Nanä" by Polo & Pan plays]

5
00:01:02,667 --> 00:01:03,833
[woman] <i>On vacation,</i>

6
00:01:05,042 --> 00:01:06,708
<i>you can be anyone you want.</i>

7
00:01:10,042 --> 00:01:12,542
<i>You can do anything you want.</i>

8
00:01:13,250 --> 00:01:15,667
<i>You can spend an entire day at the beach.</i>

9
00:01:15,750 --> 00:01:19,958
<i>Nothing but the warm sun on your face
and clear skies above.</i>

10
00:01:23,500 --> 00:01:24,500
[chuckles]

11
00:01:26,083 --> 00:01:29,458
<i>Or being on vacation</i>

12
00:01:29,542 --> 00:01:32,708
<i>transports you
into another version of yourself.</i>

13
00:01:32,792 --> 00:01:36,917
<i>Because on vacation, you strike up
conversations with fellow travelers.</i>

14
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:38,208
…his parents' place.

15
00:01:38,292 --> 00:01:40,625
[laughter]

16
00:01:40,708 --> 00:01:42,708
["Nanä" continues]

17
00:01:43,542 --> 00:01:44,667
[snickers]

18
00:01:44,750 --> 00:01:47,042
<i>You're more outgoing, more confident.</i>

19
00:01:47,125 --> 00:01:48,125
[whispers] Sorry.

20
00:01:48,875 --> 00:01:52,125
<i>No, you know what it is?
On vacation, you're free.</i>

21
00:01:52,208 --> 00:01:53,833
<i>Free to nourish your soul.</i>

22
00:01:54,625 --> 00:01:56,167
<i>Free to follow your heart.</i>

23
00:01:56,708 --> 00:02:01,708
<i>And maybe you'll get swept off your feet
by a handsome stranger.</i>

24
00:02:01,792 --> 00:02:03,792
["Nanä" continues]

25
00:02:04,833 --> 00:02:05,833
Uh...

26
00:02:06,208 --> 00:02:10,625
<i>Or maybe you just get
some much-needed alone time.</i>

27
00:02:10,708 --> 00:02:14,750
<i>Because being alone on vacation is great.</i>

28
00:02:14,833 --> 00:02:16,833
<i>There's no commitments.</i>

29
00:02:16,917 --> 00:02:18,292
<i>No expectations.</i>

30
00:02:18,375 --> 00:02:20,000
<i>Anything could happen.</i>

31
00:02:21,292 --> 00:02:23,375
<i>You're free, remember?</i>

32
00:02:24,458 --> 00:02:26,083
<i>Free to slip in that fancy shower.</i>

33
00:02:26,167 --> 00:02:27,792
- [slips]
- [thuds]

34
00:02:28,292 --> 00:02:29,833
<i>Free to lie dead for days</i>

35
00:02:29,917 --> 00:02:32,542
<i>because you put
the "do not disturb" sign up.</i>

36
00:02:32,625 --> 00:02:34,583
<i>Your corpse gradually decomposing</i>

37
00:02:34,667 --> 00:02:37,000
<i>until a cleaning lady
comments on the putrid...</i>

38
00:02:37,083 --> 00:02:38,083
[woman 2] Poppy.

39
00:02:38,167 --> 00:02:39,167
["Nanä" stops]

40
00:02:39,250 --> 00:02:40,083
Swapna.

41
00:02:40,167 --> 00:02:41,833
Did I just read the words

42
00:02:42,417 --> 00:02:45,292
"gradually decomposing" on your screen?

43
00:02:45,375 --> 00:02:46,375
No.

44
00:02:47,958 --> 00:02:49,458
Well… yeah.

45
00:02:49,958 --> 00:02:52,750
But I was just, um…
I was just trying something new.

46
00:02:52,833 --> 00:02:55,458
And this isn't done, like, at all.
It's just, um…

47
00:02:56,125 --> 00:02:59,250
It's all a part of my… process.

48
00:02:59,333 --> 00:03:01,708
- Your process is quite disturbing.
- [Poppy] Fair.

49
00:03:01,792 --> 00:03:04,667
But, I mean, don't you ever
find travel a little

50
00:03:06,250 --> 00:03:07,250
lonely?

51
00:03:07,292 --> 00:03:10,292
Poppy… [chuckles impatiently]
…need I remind you

52
00:03:10,833 --> 00:03:14,500
that you take vacations for a living.

53
00:03:15,083 --> 00:03:16,958
People would kill for this job.

54
00:03:17,042 --> 00:03:21,083
In fact, five years ago, in there,
you told me you would kill for this job.

55
00:03:21,167 --> 00:03:23,125
- I know.
- So then write like it!

56
00:03:23,208 --> 00:03:25,125
Make me burn with jealousy

57
00:03:25,208 --> 00:03:28,333
for your young, cool,
carefree, jet-setting life.

58
00:03:28,917 --> 00:03:32,833
And if I don't at least consider
leaving my husband and children

59
00:03:32,917 --> 00:03:37,292
after reading your article,
then you are not doing it right, okay?

60
00:03:37,875 --> 00:03:38,708
[Poppy] Mm-hm.

61
00:03:38,792 --> 00:03:39,917
Okay.

62
00:03:40,875 --> 00:03:41,875
[Swapna sighs]

63
00:03:41,958 --> 00:03:43,958
[pleasant ethereal music plays]

64
00:03:48,083 --> 00:03:49,917
[ethereal music becomes upbeat]

65
00:03:51,750 --> 00:03:55,125
{\an8}[Poppy] Yes,
I am back in America safe and sound.

66
00:03:55,208 --> 00:03:57,375
[woman] <i>Poppy!</i>
<i>We had no idea you were back.</i>

67
00:03:57,458 --> 00:03:59,167
I'm sorry I didn't call.

68
00:03:59,250 --> 00:04:00,250
I know.

69
00:04:00,792 --> 00:04:02,208
<i>How are the plants?</i>

70
00:04:02,292 --> 00:04:03,833
How are my plants? [Sighs]

71
00:04:03,917 --> 00:04:05,458
Mom, it's a massacre.

72
00:04:05,542 --> 00:04:08,500
There should be tribunals
about what I've done to houseplants.

73
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:13,125
Do you have any recipes that use
one shriveled lime, hot sauce,

74
00:04:13,208 --> 00:04:14,833
mustard, and no other ingredients?

75
00:04:14,917 --> 00:04:15,917
<i>What? No.</i>

76
00:04:15,958 --> 00:04:17,042
- Oh.
- [phone beeps]

77
00:04:17,917 --> 00:04:19,625
<i>Tell me, how was the trip?</i>

78
00:04:19,708 --> 00:04:20,708
[phone beeps]

79
00:04:21,500 --> 00:04:23,917
Uh, hey, I gotta go.
Yeah, I gotta go. I love you.

80
00:04:26,792 --> 00:04:27,792
[phone clicks]

81
00:04:29,125 --> 00:04:30,375
Hey, David, what's going on?

82
00:04:30,458 --> 00:04:33,917
What's going on?
Well, I'm getting married in Barcelona.

83
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:35,875
<i>Yeah, I heard that. Congratulations.</i>

84
00:04:35,958 --> 00:04:37,292
Yeah, why haven't you RSVP'd?

85
00:04:37,375 --> 00:04:39,708
<i>I sent you an invite, like, months ago.</i>

86
00:04:40,625 --> 00:04:41,667
[whispers] Shit.

87
00:04:41,750 --> 00:04:43,958
Um, yeah, I'm so sorry.

88
00:04:44,042 --> 00:04:46,083
I, um... Well, I was in Prague.

89
00:04:46,167 --> 00:04:47,708
And then Kyoto, and, um…

90
00:04:47,792 --> 00:04:49,667
<i>I gotta get back in the whole…</i>

91
00:04:49,750 --> 00:04:52,000
<i>The mail situation because, you know...</i>

92
00:04:52,083 --> 00:04:53,875
<i>But it's fine because I found it.</i>

93
00:04:54,500 --> 00:04:55,833
Wow.

94
00:04:56,542 --> 00:04:58,375
Ooh, pretty!

95
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:01,083
Shit, it's this weekend?

96
00:05:01,667 --> 00:05:03,667
<i>I'm sorry, David. I don't think I can go.</i>

97
00:05:03,750 --> 00:05:06,333
You have more airline points than God.
Just book it.

98
00:05:06,417 --> 00:05:07,958
<i>No, it's not about that.</i>

99
00:05:08,042 --> 00:05:11,292
<i>I'm supposed to be in Santorini
for this hotel opening.</i>

100
00:05:11,375 --> 00:05:12,792
Boo!

101
00:05:12,875 --> 00:05:16,208
Also, I don't really think Sarah and Alex
would want me to be there.

102
00:05:16,292 --> 00:05:18,875
Wait, he didn't tell you? They broke up.

103
00:05:20,583 --> 00:05:22,333
- Uh…
<i>- I knew things were weird.</i>

104
00:05:22,417 --> 00:05:23,875
<i>I didn't think they were that weird.</i>

105
00:05:23,958 --> 00:05:24,792
Me neither.

106
00:05:24,875 --> 00:05:26,875
<i>You were best friends.
You'll figure it out.</i>

107
00:05:26,958 --> 00:05:28,333
We've got an open bar.

108
00:05:28,417 --> 00:05:29,917
- Who is that?
- It's Poppy.

109
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:31,583
- Hi, Poppy!
- Nam says hi.

110
00:05:31,667 --> 00:05:32,792
Hi, Nam.

111
00:05:32,875 --> 00:05:34,875
[David] <i>Poppy, please,</i>
<i>you're good at a wedding.</i>

112
00:05:34,958 --> 00:05:37,125
<i>You make my family fun somehow, okay?</i>

113
00:05:37,208 --> 00:05:40,542
<i>I need you here. Whatever happened
between you and Alex, get over it.</i>

114
00:05:40,625 --> 00:05:43,000
Okay? And get your ass to Barcelona.

115
00:05:43,083 --> 00:05:45,444
- [inhales sharply] I don't… David, it's…
- [line disconnects]

116
00:05:46,542 --> 00:05:47,708
Hello? David?

117
00:05:49,208 --> 00:05:50,250
David?

118
00:05:51,083 --> 00:05:52,208
[phone clicks]

119
00:05:53,333 --> 00:05:54,375
[sighs]

120
00:05:54,458 --> 00:05:56,458
[serene music plays]

121
00:05:59,417 --> 00:06:00,417
[snickers]

122
00:06:09,833 --> 00:06:11,833
[music turns energetic]

123
00:06:22,500 --> 00:06:23,500
[Poppy] <i>Alex?</i>

124
00:06:24,083 --> 00:06:25,125
Hi!

125
00:06:25,875 --> 00:06:27,458
Hey, hey!

126
00:06:27,542 --> 00:06:28,542
Hi!

127
00:06:28,958 --> 00:06:31,750
I'm Poppy. And you're Alex, duh.

128
00:06:31,833 --> 00:06:33,833
Whoa, do you go to Boston College?

129
00:06:33,917 --> 00:06:36,042
I'm just messing with you.
I love the school spirit.

130
00:06:36,125 --> 00:06:39,333
Go… Eagles? Is it the Eagles?
I swear to God, I go here too.

131
00:06:39,417 --> 00:06:43,292
Thank you so much again for the ride.
You're much better than the bus.

132
00:06:43,375 --> 00:06:48,125
Also, I cannot believe there's
another person here from Linfield, Ohio,

133
00:06:48,208 --> 00:06:49,625
and we have never met before.

134
00:06:49,708 --> 00:06:53,417
I know you went to West Linfield
and I went to East Linfield,

135
00:06:53,500 --> 00:06:56,125
but still, crazy.

136
00:06:56,208 --> 00:06:58,583
I mean, two ships
passing in the night, right?

137
00:06:58,667 --> 00:07:00,833
Thank God Bonnie suggested we carpool.

138
00:07:00,917 --> 00:07:02,250
You're an hour late.

139
00:07:02,333 --> 00:07:03,833
Didn't you say 8:00-ish?

140
00:07:03,917 --> 00:07:05,667
Well, it's 9:00.

141
00:07:06,333 --> 00:07:07,500
And I wouldn't say "ish."

142
00:07:07,583 --> 00:07:08,958
Sorry, that's my bad.

143
00:07:09,042 --> 00:07:11,333
I had to get breakfast.
I get weird if I don't eat.

144
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:14,000
[Alex] Uh…

145
00:07:17,792 --> 00:07:18,708
What are you doing?

146
00:07:18,792 --> 00:07:21,167
You blocked my whole
field of vision, so you know...

147
00:07:21,250 --> 00:07:23,917
- Ooh! Gnarly! Are you okay?
- Yeah.

148
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:25,625
That was a good one.

149
00:07:25,708 --> 00:07:28,958
It's funny because I thought
you were firing me from our road trip.

150
00:07:29,042 --> 00:07:31,042
No, I just really wanna get on the road.

151
00:07:31,125 --> 00:07:33,458
It's a long drive.
I'd like to get ahead of the traffic.

152
00:07:33,542 --> 00:07:36,167
Dude, I'm sure we'll be fine.

153
00:07:36,250 --> 00:07:38,250
- [cars honking]
- [train horn blasting]

154
00:07:41,708 --> 00:07:43,458
[Alex sighs impatiently]

155
00:07:45,375 --> 00:07:48,125
So tell me everything.
Like, just from the top.

156
00:07:48,875 --> 00:07:50,667
Were you born in Linfield?

157
00:07:50,750 --> 00:07:52,917
Natural? C-section?

158
00:07:53,667 --> 00:07:54,667
[Alex sighs]

159
00:07:57,292 --> 00:08:00,708
Okay, I know you're mad at me,
but when you taste this breakfast burrito,

160
00:08:00,792 --> 00:08:02,167
you'll agree it was worth it.

161
00:08:02,250 --> 00:08:04,583
- I got you one too.
- I'm good. I don't wanna make a mess.

162
00:08:04,667 --> 00:08:07,833
No, seriously, I can hold it here,
and then you can take a bite.

163
00:08:07,917 --> 00:08:09,292
I'm good. Really.

164
00:08:09,375 --> 00:08:12,375
All right. Your loss, honestly.
It's the best...

165
00:08:12,458 --> 00:08:16,625
I have an idea.
Maybe we just don't talk for a little bit.

166
00:08:21,500 --> 00:08:22,833
[Poppy crinkles foil]

167
00:08:25,042 --> 00:08:26,792
- [Alex sighs]
- [Poppy chews loudly]

168
00:08:27,292 --> 00:08:28,292
[Poppy] Mm!

169
00:08:31,125 --> 00:08:32,333
It needs hot sauce.

170
00:08:35,208 --> 00:08:36,083
Can you just not...

171
00:08:36,167 --> 00:08:38,667
This Tapatío really takes it over the top.

172
00:08:42,625 --> 00:08:43,625
Oh!

173
00:08:45,292 --> 00:08:46,500
That is spicy!

174
00:08:46,583 --> 00:08:47,833
[Poppy chuckles]

175
00:08:47,917 --> 00:08:49,375
Might've overdid it.

176
00:08:52,250 --> 00:08:53,917
This will take the edge off.

177
00:08:54,583 --> 00:08:57,667
- I'm sorry, can you be careful with that?
- Dude, I got it.

178
00:08:59,500 --> 00:09:01,125
[vehicle in front moves forward]

179
00:09:02,625 --> 00:09:04,625
[Poppy keeps chewing loudly]

180
00:09:05,917 --> 00:09:06,917
[Poppy] Mm…

181
00:09:10,458 --> 00:09:11,833
[brakes squeal]

182
00:09:11,917 --> 00:09:12,917
[Alex] Oh!

183
00:09:16,958 --> 00:09:18,042
Shit.

184
00:09:31,583 --> 00:09:33,250
[Alex sighs]

185
00:09:34,750 --> 00:09:37,708
If you could be anywhere in the world now,
where would you go?

186
00:09:37,792 --> 00:09:39,625
- Right now?
- Mm-hm.

187
00:09:40,667 --> 00:09:43,792
Linfield, Ohio.
We're gonna be four hours late.

188
00:09:43,875 --> 00:09:44,917
You know what they say.

189
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:48,083
Four hours late to Linfield
is four hours well spent.

190
00:09:48,167 --> 00:09:49,875
What? Who says that?

191
00:09:49,958 --> 00:09:51,708
- What's wrong with Linfield?
- Um…

192
00:09:51,792 --> 00:09:52,917
Everything.

193
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:56,292
- Linfield was a great place to grow up.
- Ooh, hard disagree.

194
00:09:56,375 --> 00:09:58,292
My turn. I'd be in Paris.

195
00:09:59,250 --> 00:10:02,083
Having, oh, like, a little cortado.

196
00:10:02,667 --> 00:10:04,958
And a cigarette at a café.

197
00:10:05,042 --> 00:10:06,417
- You smoke?
- No.

198
00:10:07,042 --> 00:10:08,625
Paris me would smoke.

199
00:10:09,458 --> 00:10:12,042
Okay, your turn. And don't say Linfield.

200
00:10:12,625 --> 00:10:14,375
Back in Boston, I guess.

201
00:10:14,458 --> 00:10:17,125
That is so boring. Japan's my number two.

202
00:10:17,875 --> 00:10:18,875
Okay.

203
00:10:20,167 --> 00:10:21,167
Canada.

204
00:10:21,958 --> 00:10:24,792
So just to recap,
your top three destinations are

205
00:10:24,875 --> 00:10:26,708
where we are going, where we just left,

206
00:10:26,792 --> 00:10:29,417
and the more polite version of the US?

207
00:10:30,500 --> 00:10:31,500
Hm.

208
00:10:32,542 --> 00:10:35,125
- You wanna, like, play some music?
- Yeah! Oh.

209
00:10:35,208 --> 00:10:36,542
Wait, I'd be honored.

210
00:10:37,750 --> 00:10:41,417
- Jesus. Oh, sorry. I got it.
- Just be careful with that. Great.

211
00:10:42,708 --> 00:10:44,583
["Forever Your Girl" by Paula Abdul plays]

212
00:10:44,667 --> 00:10:46,333
[mouths] <i>♪ Hey, baby ♪</i>

213
00:10:46,417 --> 00:10:48,208
[sings] <i>♪ You got to remember ♪</i>

214
00:10:49,667 --> 00:10:51,875
<i>♪ I'm forever your girl ♪</i>

215
00:10:51,958 --> 00:10:53,917
[mumbles] <i>♪ Baby, forever ♪</i>

216
00:10:54,417 --> 00:10:55,875
<i>♪ And ever and ever ♪</i>

217
00:10:56,375 --> 00:10:58,708
[speaks] <i>♪ You know I am… ♪</i>

218
00:11:07,333 --> 00:11:10,875
You hate this song.
How is it possible you hate this song?

219
00:11:10,958 --> 00:11:12,458
It's just the saxophone.

220
00:11:12,542 --> 00:11:14,417
What do you have against saxophone?

221
00:11:14,500 --> 00:11:18,708
Name a single song that has been improved
by the appearance of a saxophone. One.

222
00:11:18,792 --> 00:11:20,625
I can name literally hundreds.

223
00:11:20,708 --> 00:11:22,708
- Right.
- And that's just the Kenny G catalog.

224
00:11:22,792 --> 00:11:25,125
- You've gotta be kidding.
- What else do you hate?

225
00:11:26,417 --> 00:11:27,958
- Come on.
- Flip-flops.

226
00:11:28,042 --> 00:11:29,375
- Flip-flops?!
- Yeah.

227
00:11:29,458 --> 00:11:31,000
- Okay.
- Christmas music.

228
00:11:31,083 --> 00:11:33,208
- What?
- Reality TV.

229
00:11:33,292 --> 00:11:34,958
- [scoffs]
- Holding hands.

230
00:11:35,500 --> 00:11:37,583
I literally love all of those.

231
00:11:37,667 --> 00:11:39,708
Yeah. I bet you love everything.

232
00:11:39,792 --> 00:11:40,792
Yeah.

233
00:11:41,417 --> 00:11:43,500
No, it's not true. I hate running.

234
00:11:43,583 --> 00:11:45,167
[laughs]

235
00:11:45,250 --> 00:11:46,375
What?

236
00:11:47,667 --> 00:11:48,667
I love running.

237
00:11:50,250 --> 00:11:54,375
Well, let's face it, Alex.
You and I are not meant to be together.

238
00:11:54,958 --> 00:11:55,958
Um…

239
00:11:56,625 --> 00:11:59,125
I have a girlfriend, so…

240
00:11:59,750 --> 00:12:00,875
That's so cool.

241
00:12:01,625 --> 00:12:03,083
<i>♪ He promised the world… ♪</i>

242
00:12:03,167 --> 00:12:05,083
Doesn't mean we can't enjoy a little…

243
00:12:06,417 --> 00:12:08,542
- Casual sax.
- [turns up volume]

244
00:12:15,708 --> 00:12:17,292
["Forever Your Girl" fades out]

245
00:12:20,958 --> 00:12:22,958
I'm gonna get a coffee.
Do you want anything?

246
00:12:23,042 --> 00:12:24,042
- I'm good.
- Okay.

247
00:13:02,542 --> 00:13:03,542
What are you doing?

248
00:13:04,083 --> 00:13:05,083
Isn't it great?

249
00:13:07,208 --> 00:13:08,208
It's a well.

250
00:13:08,583 --> 00:13:10,542
It's a friggin' wishing well

251
00:13:10,625 --> 00:13:13,125
next to a gas station
in the middle of nowhere.

252
00:13:14,125 --> 00:13:15,875
You gonna make a wish?

253
00:13:16,375 --> 00:13:17,750
I don't have any money.

254
00:13:18,750 --> 00:13:19,750
[Alex scoffs]

255
00:13:20,417 --> 00:13:21,875
[Alex sucks his teeth]

256
00:13:21,958 --> 00:13:23,625
[soft ethereal music plays]

257
00:13:23,708 --> 00:13:24,708
Thanks.

258
00:13:30,500 --> 00:13:31,667
[coin dings]

259
00:13:31,750 --> 00:13:32,750
[Poppy chuckles]

260
00:13:33,458 --> 00:13:34,458
Okay, your turn.

261
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:37,458
- That was my only coin.
- What? Why didn't you tell me?

262
00:13:37,542 --> 00:13:40,042
- I took your wish.
- It's fine. Come on.

263
00:13:40,542 --> 00:13:43,375
- You wanna know what I wished for?
- Doesn't work like that.

264
00:13:43,917 --> 00:13:44,917
Come on.

265
00:13:47,792 --> 00:13:50,000
- [Poppy] But I really wanna tell you.
- [Alex] Nope.

266
00:14:00,208 --> 00:14:01,208
What?

267
00:14:05,167 --> 00:14:07,250
- Did you lock the car?
- Yeah.

268
00:14:07,750 --> 00:14:11,125
I didn't want anyone to steal it.
I thought you had the keys!

269
00:14:11,208 --> 00:14:12,958
- Oh my God!
- I…

270
00:14:14,625 --> 00:14:18,375
- Oh… no.
- [sighs]

271
00:14:22,833 --> 00:14:24,667
[Alex blows raspberry]

272
00:14:26,792 --> 00:14:31,542
Maybe Triple-A isn't here yet because
they locked their keys in their truck.

273
00:14:32,708 --> 00:14:34,125
And who would they call?

274
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:36,125
Quadruple-A?

275
00:14:45,042 --> 00:14:46,042
[Alex sighs]

276
00:14:56,167 --> 00:14:57,167
Hi.

277
00:14:57,250 --> 00:14:59,542
Two of your finest rooms, please.

278
00:14:59,625 --> 00:15:00,667
Cheapest.

279
00:15:00,750 --> 00:15:03,458
Oh, you're in luck.
We got two rooms available.

280
00:15:03,542 --> 00:15:05,667
Room 106 and, uh…

281
00:15:06,833 --> 00:15:07,833
Hold up.

282
00:15:07,875 --> 00:15:10,875
Hey, Phil, what's the status
of the big stain in 108?

283
00:15:10,958 --> 00:15:12,917
- We'll just take 106.
- We'll just take 106.

284
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:13,917
Yeah.

285
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:17,833
No, Dad, you don't need to drive
five hours to Pennsylvania to pick me up.

286
00:15:17,917 --> 00:15:19,958
Yeah, I can't wait to see you.

287
00:15:20,042 --> 00:15:22,583
[Poppy] Yes. Alex is a male Alex.

288
00:15:23,167 --> 00:15:25,333
I'm 95% sure he's not a murderer.

289
00:15:25,417 --> 00:15:26,417
Actually…

290
00:15:26,500 --> 00:15:28,917
Hey, Alex's girlfriend, is he a murderer?

291
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:31,833
- She's just kidding. Ignore her.
- He dodged the question.

292
00:15:31,917 --> 00:15:34,708
I'll sleep on the floor. I promise.

293
00:15:34,792 --> 00:15:36,375
He's a Virgo, so probably not.

294
00:15:36,458 --> 00:15:39,167
- [Alex] I'll see you tomorrow. Bye.
- Okay. Love you. Bye.

295
00:15:39,250 --> 00:15:41,500
Wait, so your girlfriend's from Linfield?

296
00:15:41,583 --> 00:15:42,583
Yeah.

297
00:15:42,917 --> 00:15:44,375
High school sweethearts?

298
00:15:44,458 --> 00:15:45,667
[Alex] Mm-hm.

299
00:15:45,750 --> 00:15:47,042
Good for you.

300
00:15:47,667 --> 00:15:51,708
Yeah, you know, we like the same things.
Our families are close. It's nice.

301
00:15:51,792 --> 00:15:54,292
Hey, if Mom likes her, she's a keeper.

302
00:15:56,417 --> 00:15:58,417
My mom never met Sarah.

303
00:16:00,333 --> 00:16:01,958
She died when I was little.

304
00:16:06,292 --> 00:16:07,875
[sighs, whispers] Shit.

305
00:16:14,375 --> 00:16:17,000
Can't even imagine.
That must've been really hard.

306
00:16:17,083 --> 00:16:19,167
My brother and I were pretty young.

307
00:16:20,292 --> 00:16:21,750
It was worse for my dad.

308
00:16:23,125 --> 00:16:25,750
Took him a long time
before he was, you know…

309
00:16:27,083 --> 00:16:28,083
Normal.

310
00:16:29,542 --> 00:16:30,958
My grandma helped a lot.

311
00:16:34,292 --> 00:16:37,083
- Sure you don't wanna sleep head to toe?
- No, I'm fine.

312
00:16:37,167 --> 00:16:38,167
Okay.

313
00:16:48,500 --> 00:16:49,500
[Alex sighs]

314
00:16:51,750 --> 00:16:53,875
So what is it with you and Linfield?

315
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:56,000
[Poppy chuckles]

316
00:16:57,875 --> 00:16:59,333
Um… [sighs]

317
00:17:03,458 --> 00:17:05,167
We moved there when I was 11.

318
00:17:09,375 --> 00:17:11,250
And I was just so lonely.

319
00:17:12,792 --> 00:17:15,292
I was always on the outside of everything.

320
00:17:16,042 --> 00:17:18,917
And finally, I got invited to this party.

321
00:17:20,208 --> 00:17:21,750
Right before high school.

322
00:17:25,125 --> 00:17:26,958
Played Seven Minutes in Heaven.

323
00:17:29,667 --> 00:17:31,875
Brian Kelvey kissed me.

324
00:17:33,042 --> 00:17:34,458
Horrible experience.

325
00:17:34,542 --> 00:17:35,542
[snickers]

326
00:17:36,292 --> 00:17:37,667
The next day at school,

327
00:17:39,208 --> 00:17:40,875
everyone was laughing at me.

328
00:17:43,792 --> 00:17:44,917
It turns out…

329
00:17:47,417 --> 00:17:49,375
He told everyone that I blew him.

330
00:17:51,208 --> 00:17:53,125
[sad music plays]

331
00:17:53,208 --> 00:17:56,625
Over the next three years,
I was Porny Poppy.

332
00:17:58,083 --> 00:17:59,542
That's awful.

333
00:18:00,208 --> 00:18:01,458
Screw those guys.

334
00:18:01,542 --> 00:18:04,125
That's the problem with small towns.

335
00:18:06,500 --> 00:18:08,667
Once people decide who you are, that's it.

336
00:18:10,042 --> 00:18:11,167
Hm.

337
00:18:11,250 --> 00:18:12,917
That's why I wanna travel.

338
00:18:16,708 --> 00:18:20,292
You can actually be who you wanna be
instead of who they say you are.

339
00:18:21,375 --> 00:18:23,167
You know, for what it's worth,

340
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:26,542
if I'd have known you,
I wouldn't have called you that.

341
00:18:28,458 --> 00:18:30,375
You know, I think I believe you.

342
00:18:34,542 --> 00:18:35,583
And thanks.

343
00:18:36,500 --> 00:18:37,542
For what?

344
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:41,542
For being the first person
who I've told that story to

345
00:18:41,625 --> 00:18:43,542
who didn't ask whether I did it.

346
00:18:48,542 --> 00:18:49,750
Good night, Poppy.

347
00:18:51,458 --> 00:18:52,542
Good night, Alex.

348
00:18:56,417 --> 00:18:58,583
["That's How I Got to Memphis"
by Tom T. Hall plays]

349
00:19:01,792 --> 00:19:04,458
I can't believe you went
on a freaking run this morning.

350
00:19:04,542 --> 00:19:05,917
I thought you ditched me.

351
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:09,250
I was this close to hitchhiking
with some me thy trucker.

352
00:19:09,333 --> 00:19:11,750
[Alex] Oh, a me thy one.
That's smart. Fast drivers.

353
00:19:11,833 --> 00:19:13,500
[Poppy laughs]

354
00:19:13,583 --> 00:19:16,667
Nevertheless, I am happy
that I didn't scare you off.

355
00:19:16,750 --> 00:19:19,708
You're terrifying for many reasons,
but you're four feet tall.

356
00:19:19,792 --> 00:19:21,292
- You don't scare me.
- Hey!

357
00:19:21,375 --> 00:19:23,208
I'm small, but fierce.

358
00:19:23,292 --> 00:19:24,708
- You're a tiny fighter.
- [gasps]

359
00:19:24,792 --> 00:19:25,917
Wait.

360
00:19:26,625 --> 00:19:27,625
I like that.

361
00:19:27,667 --> 00:19:29,292
[both laugh]

362
00:19:29,875 --> 00:19:32,750
Okay, so considering the last 24 hours,

363
00:19:33,292 --> 00:19:36,542
where does Alex Nilsen stand on travel?

364
00:19:36,625 --> 00:19:39,167
Love or hate?

365
00:19:40,292 --> 00:19:42,250
I mean,
I've never really traveled anywhere.

366
00:19:44,583 --> 00:19:46,250
But, this morning,

367
00:19:48,042 --> 00:19:52,542
I saw this beautiful sunrise
over this place I've never been before.

368
00:19:52,625 --> 00:19:54,833
[contemplative music plays]

369
00:19:54,917 --> 00:19:58,125
And I wouldn't have if everything
had gone according to plan, so

370
00:20:00,708 --> 00:20:01,708
love.

371
00:20:02,542 --> 00:20:03,833
I'm thinking love.

372
00:20:03,917 --> 00:20:04,917
Okay.

373
00:20:06,208 --> 00:20:08,958
So should we detour
this road trip to Canada right now?

374
00:20:09,042 --> 00:20:10,792
I know it's at the top of your list.

375
00:20:10,875 --> 00:20:12,542
Let's try being friends first.

376
00:20:12,625 --> 00:20:13,625
Fair.

377
00:20:17,708 --> 00:20:19,333
Friends do not shake hands.

378
00:20:23,250 --> 00:20:24,250
Nice.

379
00:20:25,125 --> 00:20:26,125
[Poppy giggles]

380
00:20:29,417 --> 00:20:31,083
[instructor] <i>Is that the best you can do?</i>

381
00:20:31,167 --> 00:20:33,875
{\an8}- ["Ani Kuni" by Polo & Pan plays]
- Get those booties in the air!

382
00:20:34,500 --> 00:20:36,000
{\an8}Keep it up! Keep it up!

383
00:20:36,583 --> 00:20:38,125
I can't go to the wedding.

384
00:20:39,083 --> 00:20:40,083
Right?

385
00:20:41,333 --> 00:20:42,333
Right.

386
00:20:42,875 --> 00:20:43,875
That'd be crazy.

387
00:20:43,917 --> 00:20:45,042
Insane.

388
00:20:45,125 --> 00:20:49,208
And also, I have Santorini,
so I don't even need to make up an excuse.

389
00:20:49,292 --> 00:20:51,208
- 'Cause I already have an excuse.
- Yup.

390
00:20:51,292 --> 00:20:52,292
And back down.

391
00:20:52,375 --> 00:20:53,458
Oh, thank God.

392
00:20:54,125 --> 00:20:57,333
But maybe the universe
is giving me a sign.

393
00:20:57,417 --> 00:20:58,708
No, it's not.

394
00:20:58,792 --> 00:21:01,417
- This is you in a rut trying to go back...
- What?

395
00:21:01,500 --> 00:21:03,875
This is you in a rut
trying to go back in time

396
00:21:03,958 --> 00:21:06,625
to fix a friendship
that blew up in your face!

397
00:21:06,708 --> 00:21:07,542
[Poppy] That's harsh.

398
00:21:07,625 --> 00:21:08,917
["Ani Kuni" continues]

399
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:11,458
- You're getting me in trouble.
- What are we, ten?

400
00:21:11,542 --> 00:21:12,667
No one can hear us.

401
00:21:12,750 --> 00:21:14,792
Everyone can hear you.

402
00:21:15,292 --> 00:21:18,000
- Back up. Take it to the max.
- [mouths] Oh…

403
00:21:19,667 --> 00:21:20,792
[instructor] Now!

404
00:21:20,875 --> 00:21:22,750
Don't feel like talking now, do we?

405
00:21:23,333 --> 00:21:24,792
[woman 1] Seriously? Like…

406
00:21:25,417 --> 00:21:27,583
- [panting] Screw this.
- I know, right?

407
00:21:27,667 --> 00:21:31,042
Like, it's torture and it's expensive,
but I'll be back Monday.

408
00:21:32,917 --> 00:21:34,083
What are you doing?

409
00:21:34,167 --> 00:21:35,792
- I'm gonna call Alex.
- Now?

410
00:21:35,875 --> 00:21:38,833
Mm-hm. Post-workout adrenaline.
If I wait, I'm gonna chicken out.

411
00:21:38,917 --> 00:21:41,458
Okay, so I'm just gonna tell him
that I'm not going.

412
00:21:41,542 --> 00:21:44,125
- So he doesn't think it's because of him.
- Yeah, totally.

413
00:21:45,083 --> 00:21:46,667
- [line rings]
- It's ringing.

414
00:21:47,708 --> 00:21:49,625
Wait, how'd you do the foot thingy?

415
00:21:49,708 --> 00:21:51,458
- Wiggle and pull.
- I'm wiggling and pulling.

416
00:21:51,542 --> 00:21:52,742
- Can you help me?
- Just wiggle…

417
00:21:52,792 --> 00:21:53,792
[ringtone plays]

418
00:21:54,875 --> 00:21:55,875
Hello?

419
00:21:56,250 --> 00:21:58,625
- Help me. I'm wiggling.
- [woman 2] Wiggle harder!

420
00:21:58,708 --> 00:21:59,792
[Poppy] I'm pulling, dude.

421
00:21:59,875 --> 00:22:00,917
[Alex] <i>Hello?</i>

422
00:22:02,458 --> 00:22:03,917
<i>- Poppy?</i>
- [woman 2 whispers] What?

423
00:22:04,000 --> 00:22:05,083
Sorry, who's this?

424
00:22:05,792 --> 00:22:06,917
You called me.

425
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:08,250
[whispers] Speaker.

426
00:22:09,458 --> 00:22:11,042
Yes, I did. I did.

427
00:22:11,667 --> 00:22:13,750
Is this about my brother's wedding?

428
00:22:13,833 --> 00:22:16,375
[clears throat] <i>Yeah.</i>
<i>Uh, yeah. So here's the thing.</i>

429
00:22:16,458 --> 00:22:19,875
The issue is I have a work thing
this weekend, so…

430
00:22:20,542 --> 00:22:21,542
Okay.

431
00:22:21,583 --> 00:22:24,583
Yeah, okay, well,
that's probably for the best.

432
00:22:24,667 --> 00:22:26,000
[mouths] For the best?

433
00:22:26,083 --> 00:22:30,708
I just mean David's super stressed
about the seating arrangements, so it's…

434
00:22:32,250 --> 00:22:34,292
<i>So where is </i>R&R <i>sending you this time?</i>

435
00:22:34,375 --> 00:22:35,375
[whispers] Santorini.

436
00:22:35,875 --> 00:22:36,875
[slowly] Santorini.

437
00:22:37,708 --> 00:22:39,208
- Poppy…
- Barcelona.

438
00:22:39,292 --> 00:22:40,292
[woman 2 gasps]

439
00:22:40,375 --> 00:22:41,708
<i>- What?</i>
- God, give me that!

440
00:22:41,792 --> 00:22:44,750
Yeah, it's so funny.
It's such a… It's a crazy coincidence.

441
00:22:44,833 --> 00:22:48,125
<i>R&R </i>is doing this whole feature
on Barcelona.

442
00:22:48,208 --> 00:22:51,167
- Oh, really?
- And I can attend the wedding.

443
00:22:51,792 --> 00:22:53,708
- [mutes phone]
<i>- Okay. Wow. Cool.</i>

444
00:22:54,750 --> 00:22:56,351
- What are you doing?
- What? I don't know!

445
00:22:56,375 --> 00:22:58,625
- What are you doing?
- It just came out! I don't know!

446
00:22:58,708 --> 00:23:01,375
Tell him you're actually
going to Santorini...

447
00:23:03,417 --> 00:23:04,667
Are you still there?

448
00:23:04,750 --> 00:23:06,500
- Yeah, but...
- Shut up. Sh... sh... sh.

449
00:23:10,917 --> 00:23:13,417
- [unmutes phone]
- Looking forward to catching up, buddy.

450
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:15,000
[whispers] Buddy?

451
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:17,792
Okay, well, I'll…

452
00:23:18,667 --> 00:23:19,750
I'll see you soon.

453
00:23:21,042 --> 00:23:22,042
Bye.

454
00:23:22,125 --> 00:23:23,042
[hangs up]

455
00:23:23,125 --> 00:23:26,458
Wow. Deep down in my heart,
I knew that was gonna happen.

456
00:23:26,542 --> 00:23:28,750
[peppy music plays]

457
00:23:32,042 --> 00:23:34,583
Where is this wedding anyway?
Please say somewhere nice.

458
00:23:34,667 --> 00:23:35,667
Barcelona.

459
00:23:36,625 --> 00:23:41,250
Fine, then I will expect an article
about destination weddings in Barcelona

460
00:23:41,333 --> 00:23:43,500
in my inbox when you get back.

461
00:23:43,583 --> 00:23:44,458
Thank you.

462
00:23:44,542 --> 00:23:45,542
[Swapna] Mm.

463
00:23:46,667 --> 00:23:48,625
- I know lately I've been...
- Bad at your job?

464
00:23:48,708 --> 00:23:49,917
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

465
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:53,083
But I think that this might…
help with that.

466
00:23:53,167 --> 00:23:54,208
Well, good.

467
00:23:54,292 --> 00:23:56,917
Because I miss my favorite writer.

468
00:23:57,792 --> 00:23:59,708
Now go away.

469
00:23:59,792 --> 00:24:00,875
[softly] Okay.

470
00:24:05,625 --> 00:24:07,625
["Hang with Me" by Robyn plays]

471
00:24:14,292 --> 00:24:17,292
<i>♪ Will you tell me once again ♪</i>

472
00:24:18,458 --> 00:24:21,625
<i>♪ How we're gonna be just friends? ♪</i>

473
00:24:22,333 --> 00:24:25,375
[Poppy sings]
<i>♪ If you're for real and not pretend ♪</i>

474
00:24:25,458 --> 00:24:30,542
<i>♪ I guess you can hang with me ♪</i>

475
00:24:30,625 --> 00:24:34,417
<i>♪ When my patience's wearing thin ♪</i>

476
00:24:35,167 --> 00:24:38,500
<i>♪ And I'm ready to give in ♪</i>

477
00:24:39,333 --> 00:24:42,250
<i>♪ Will you pick me up again? ♪</i>

478
00:24:42,333 --> 00:24:46,583
<i>♪ Then I guess you can hang with me… ♪</i>

479
00:24:46,667 --> 00:24:47,667
Ah!

480
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:49,458
[sings] <i>♪ And if you do me right ♪</i>

481
00:24:49,542 --> 00:24:51,917
<i>♪ Then I'mma do right by you ♪</i>

482
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:54,000
<i>♪ And if you keep it tight ♪</i>

483
00:24:54,083 --> 00:24:55,708
<i>♪ Then I'm gonna confide in you ♪</i>

484
00:24:55,792 --> 00:25:02,250
- [song ends]
- [scatting] <i>♪ If you hang with… ♪</i>

485
00:25:04,583 --> 00:25:05,583
Hi.

486
00:25:06,167 --> 00:25:07,708
- Hi.
- [Poppy] Alex.

487
00:25:08,542 --> 00:25:11,208
I was not expecting to see you… yet.

488
00:25:11,292 --> 00:25:13,000
Uh, yeah, I just landed.

489
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:15,500
You were singing pretty loud.

490
00:25:15,583 --> 00:25:18,417
Yeah, my bag came out first, and that…

491
00:25:19,042 --> 00:25:20,625
- Never happens.
- [Alex] Huh.

492
00:25:22,500 --> 00:25:23,500
Cool.

493
00:25:26,125 --> 00:25:27,125
Uh…

494
00:25:28,250 --> 00:25:29,333
Long time no see.

495
00:25:29,833 --> 00:25:31,917
It's been a couple of years.

496
00:25:34,417 --> 00:25:35,417
Well…

497
00:25:37,333 --> 00:25:40,083
Oh, you're offering me a handshake.

498
00:25:40,167 --> 00:25:41,917
I just didn't know what was…

499
00:25:43,083 --> 00:25:44,083
Uh…

500
00:25:44,708 --> 00:25:45,833
You know, appropriate.

501
00:25:47,583 --> 00:25:51,125
[sighs] This is really weird.
It's very hard for me not to hug you.

502
00:25:52,500 --> 00:25:55,708
Because I come
from a very hug-forward family.

503
