Vacation Alex!

754
00:38:07,375 --> 00:38:08,708
Come on!

755
00:38:15,750 --> 00:38:17,250
["Esperar Pra Ver" fades out]

756
00:38:23,958 --> 00:38:25,167
[Poppy] Come on.

757
00:38:25,708 --> 00:38:27,292
- [driver gasps]
- [Poppy] Mm…

758
00:38:29,333 --> 00:38:30,333
Jesus.

759
00:38:31,167 --> 00:38:33,167
- That is an intense tattoo.
- No.

760
00:38:34,208 --> 00:38:36,167
This is <i>Memento Mori</i>.

761
00:38:37,542 --> 00:38:40,917
It's Latin for "remember you must die."

762
00:38:41,417 --> 00:38:43,458
Because we're gonna die.

763
00:38:43,958 --> 00:38:45,500
You are gonna die.

764
00:38:47,333 --> 00:38:49,250
[quietly] Cool. Cool.

765
00:38:49,333 --> 00:38:50,333
[driver] Yeah.

766
00:38:51,083 --> 00:38:53,083
["Esperar Pra Ver" continues]

767
00:38:53,792 --> 00:38:54,833
[Daisy] Hey.

768
00:38:54,917 --> 00:38:55,917
Oh, hey.

769
00:38:55,958 --> 00:38:57,958
[Daisy laughs, pants]

770
00:39:08,208 --> 00:39:10,250
[man] Let's go cliff diving!

771
00:39:10,875 --> 00:39:12,375
This will blow your mind.

772
00:39:13,125 --> 00:39:14,125
Okay.

773
00:39:17,583 --> 00:39:18,875
Wait up. I'm coming.

774
00:39:44,958 --> 00:39:46,208
Oh, shit.

775
00:39:52,375 --> 00:39:54,417
[mysterious music plays]

776
00:39:59,792 --> 00:40:02,250
Whoa. [Pants]

777
00:40:13,917 --> 00:40:14,750
[Alex] Poppy?

778
00:40:14,833 --> 00:40:16,708
The tents all look the same.

779
00:40:19,917 --> 00:40:21,500
- Poppy?
- [man] Shh!

780
00:40:21,583 --> 00:40:22,708
Sorry. Sorry.

781
00:40:25,625 --> 00:40:28,292
Are you… [kisses] Are you… Are you okay?

782
00:40:28,375 --> 00:40:30,083
- [Poppy] Mm-hm.
- You seem a little off.

783
00:40:30,167 --> 00:40:31,167
- Sorry.
- What?

784
00:40:31,208 --> 00:40:34,083
- Oh, no.
- No, you can tell me.

785
00:40:35,625 --> 00:40:38,333
I just can't stop thinking about death.

786
00:40:39,333 --> 00:40:40,333
Right. Okay.

787
00:40:40,417 --> 00:40:42,583
- Would it help if I put a shirt back on?
- Yeah!

788
00:40:42,667 --> 00:40:46,917
Maybe that'll get you out of your head
and into your body.

789
00:40:47,000 --> 00:40:49,000
[Poppy and the driver keep chatting]

790
00:40:50,542 --> 00:40:51,542
[whispers] Poppy?

791
00:40:53,542 --> 00:40:54,542
Poppy?

792
00:40:55,125 --> 00:40:56,792
I think I heard your friend.

793
00:40:56,875 --> 00:40:57,875
[Alex] Poppy?

794
00:40:59,458 --> 00:41:03,125
Yeah, I think he needs my help.

795
00:41:03,208 --> 00:41:05,292
I don't know.
I think he's gonna be all right.

796
00:41:05,375 --> 00:41:06,875
He's with Daisy. He's good.

797
00:41:06,958 --> 00:41:07,958
Poppy!

798
00:41:09,292 --> 00:41:12,750
What if I don't go, and he dies?

799
00:41:13,792 --> 00:41:15,792
I mean, it might just be his time.

800
00:41:15,875 --> 00:41:16,875
[Poppy gasps]

801
00:41:16,917 --> 00:41:18,500
No, I'm kidding.

802
00:41:18,583 --> 00:41:21,042
No, but you should help him.
He doesn't sound good at all.

803
00:41:21,125 --> 00:41:22,375
- Yeah, okay.
- Yeah.

804
00:41:23,292 --> 00:41:25,667
[whispers] Alex. Alex.

805
00:41:26,875 --> 00:41:29,208
[yelps] Why are you naked?!

806
00:41:29,292 --> 00:41:31,750
[whispers] My clothes are out at sea.

807
00:41:31,833 --> 00:41:32,917
What?

808
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:34,458
[louder] My clothes are out at sea.

809
00:41:34,542 --> 00:41:36,625
Okay. What do you want me to do?

810
00:41:36,708 --> 00:41:37,708
I need clothes!

811
00:41:38,542 --> 00:41:39,542
Now.

812
00:41:40,167 --> 00:41:42,000
Okay. Okay.

813
00:41:42,083 --> 00:41:43,542
Just anything. Anything.

814
00:41:44,667 --> 00:41:46,000
- [Alex grunts]
- Sorry!

815
00:41:46,083 --> 00:41:47,417
[Alex] What even is this?

816
00:41:47,500 --> 00:41:50,625
[Poppy] It's a romper. It's like overalls.

817
00:41:50,708 --> 00:41:54,333
- What are you looking at?
- Full moon, man. [Giggles]

818
00:41:55,333 --> 00:41:57,333
[panting]

819
00:42:00,708 --> 00:42:02,083
You're ripped?

820
00:42:02,167 --> 00:42:03,167
What?

821
00:42:03,542 --> 00:42:04,708
No, shut up.

822
00:42:06,333 --> 00:42:07,708
Who would've thought?

823
00:42:08,375 --> 00:42:11,417
Vacation Alex wears women's clothes.
[chuckles]

824
00:42:11,500 --> 00:42:13,667
[laughs]

825
00:42:13,750 --> 00:42:16,708
What is that? What is that?

826
00:42:17,333 --> 00:42:18,417
What... Ew!

827
00:42:19,625 --> 00:42:21,750
Disgusting. Go away. Go in the tent.

828
00:42:21,833 --> 00:42:24,333
- I don't know which one is our tent.
- I don't know.

829
00:42:25,333 --> 00:42:26,708
[Alex] Hey, Poppy.

830
00:42:26,792 --> 00:42:27,792
[Poppy] Yeah?

831
00:42:29,000 --> 00:42:31,208
I'm sorry I ruined your night with Buck.

832
00:42:31,292 --> 00:42:33,542
You didn't ruin anything.

833
00:42:33,625 --> 00:42:37,875
I couldn't stop thinking about
my grandpa's open-casket funeral.

834
00:42:38,958 --> 00:42:39,958
What?

835
00:42:40,375 --> 00:42:42,958
It's a long story.
I'll tell you about it later.

836
00:42:44,458 --> 00:42:46,958
- You are my weirdest friend.
- [Poppy chuckles]

837
00:42:47,625 --> 00:42:49,583
And don't you forget it.

838
00:42:56,000 --> 00:42:58,000
[gentle music plays]

839
00:43:00,750 --> 00:43:03,792
Would we still be friends
if we didn't go to the same college?

840
00:43:05,208 --> 00:43:06,292
You mean like…

841
00:43:08,458 --> 00:43:09,667
After we graduate?

842
00:43:10,250 --> 00:43:11,292
I mean like…

843
00:43:12,500 --> 00:43:13,750
Hypothetically.

844
00:43:15,542 --> 00:43:17,583
If I didn't go back next semester,

845
00:43:19,250 --> 00:43:22,792
and I used my tuition
to get a terrible apartment in New York

846
00:43:23,292 --> 00:43:25,708
and intern at a magazine
and work on my blog.

847
00:43:26,792 --> 00:43:29,583
That's a very specific hypothetical.

848
00:43:29,667 --> 00:43:31,583
Would I ever see you again?

849
00:43:36,125 --> 00:43:37,250
How about this?

850
00:43:39,542 --> 00:43:40,667
Every summer,

851
00:43:41,250 --> 00:43:42,792
wherever we are,

852
00:43:43,667 --> 00:43:44,917
whatever we're doing,

853
00:43:45,625 --> 00:43:47,042
whoever we're with…

854
00:43:49,542 --> 00:43:53,167
We meet somewhere in the world for a trip.

855
00:43:57,625 --> 00:43:58,625
Deal.

856
00:44:00,333 --> 00:44:02,125
[both chuckle]

857
00:44:09,417 --> 00:44:10,708
[both laughing]

858
00:44:10,792 --> 00:44:12,250
[plane engine roars]

859
00:44:13,375 --> 00:44:14,495
[Poppy] How was your flight?

860
00:44:14,542 --> 00:44:17,375
[Alex] Yeah, it was good.
I just slept most of the time.

861
00:44:17,458 --> 00:44:18,458
Smart.

862
00:44:22,667 --> 00:44:24,667
Do you maybe wanna share a taxi?

863
00:44:24,750 --> 00:44:25,833
I rented a car.

864
00:44:25,917 --> 00:44:27,125
Oh, cool.

865
00:44:32,167 --> 00:44:33,292
Do you want a ride?

866
00:44:34,208 --> 00:44:38,667
["I Don't Know What I Can Save You From"
by Kings of Convenience plays]

867
00:44:43,625 --> 00:44:45,833
<i>♪ You called me after midnight ♪</i>

868
00:44:45,917 --> 00:44:51,167
<i>♪ Must have been three years
Since we last spoke ♪</i>

869
00:44:52,417 --> 00:44:54,583
<i>♪ I slowly tried to bring back ♪</i>

870
00:44:54,667 --> 00:44:59,208
<i>♪ The image of your face
From the memories so old… ♪</i>

871
00:44:59,292 --> 00:45:01,417
It's hotter than I thought
it was gonna be.

872
00:45:01,500 --> 00:45:04,208
Yeah. Linfield too.

873
00:45:04,292 --> 00:45:06,958
It's the hottest summer
we've had in years, apparently.

874
00:45:10,250 --> 00:45:13,208
[Alex exhales]

875
00:45:13,292 --> 00:45:16,000
[sighs] Oh man, Alex. This is bleak.

876
00:45:17,542 --> 00:45:20,208
How did we become people
who talk about the weather?

877
00:45:21,333 --> 00:45:23,583
Does this mean
that we're officially grown-ups?

878
00:45:24,083 --> 00:45:25,625
[both chuckle]

879
00:45:25,708 --> 00:45:29,542
I'm actually in the middle of redoing
the HVAC system in my house.

880
00:45:31,708 --> 00:45:33,042
Wait, you own a house?

881
00:45:33,792 --> 00:45:37,458
It's, uh, it's Grandma Betty's, actually.

882
00:45:38,500 --> 00:45:39,667
She left it to me.

883
00:45:42,917 --> 00:45:44,000
Is Betty gone?

884
00:45:45,333 --> 00:45:46,667
You know, she was old.

885
00:45:48,167 --> 00:45:49,292
It was peaceful.

886
00:45:55,250 --> 00:45:56,583
You can just leave it.

887
00:45:56,667 --> 00:45:58,917
No, seriously, you don't need
to bring my bags in.

888
00:45:59,000 --> 00:46:01,208
- Just go do wedding stuff.
- [Alex] It's fine.

889
00:46:03,500 --> 00:46:05,000
[Alex grunts]

890
00:46:05,833 --> 00:46:06,833
Wow.

891
00:46:12,083 --> 00:46:13,375
It's like a sauna in here.

892
00:46:13,458 --> 00:46:15,667
It says it's 32 degrees. Is that bad?

893
00:46:15,750 --> 00:46:17,333
That's like 90 degrees.

894
00:46:19,042 --> 00:46:20,125
Right. Bad.

895
00:46:21,583 --> 00:46:25,333
Okay, well, maybe I'll open some windows.

896
00:46:26,500 --> 00:46:29,500
[control beeps]

897
00:46:36,000 --> 00:46:37,000
Or not.

898
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:40,458
I'm leaving a very negative review
upon checkout.

899
00:46:41,625 --> 00:46:43,792
[Alex] I think this thing is broken.

900
00:46:43,875 --> 00:46:46,792
No, it says the AC does work.

901
00:46:46,875 --> 00:46:50,708
"You must lower it one degree at a time
and let it rest in between."

902
00:46:50,792 --> 00:46:53,833
- What does that mean?
- I don't know, I'm just reading the paper.

903
00:46:55,167 --> 00:46:56,167
Okay.

904
00:46:56,208 --> 00:46:57,875
[rapid beeping]

905
00:46:58,375 --> 00:46:59,917
One degree at a time.

906
00:47:00,417 --> 00:47:01,833
[quick beeps, long beep]

907
00:47:01,917 --> 00:47:04,000
Oh, wait, maybe that did something.

908
00:47:05,542 --> 00:47:06,375
No.

909
00:47:06,458 --> 00:47:09,750
Hey, you don't need to stick around.
This is gonna take a while, so…

910
00:47:09,833 --> 00:47:11,750
This is ridiculous. I'm just gonna fix it.

911
00:47:11,833 --> 00:47:15,208
Well, I'm going on the record to say
I did not ask you to do this for me.

912
00:47:15,292 --> 00:47:16,917
Well, if you die of heat stroke,

913
00:47:17,000 --> 00:47:20,250
the seating arrangement's gonna be
messed up, and David will be furious.

914
00:47:20,333 --> 00:47:23,250
Of course. Well, at least it's a dry heat.

915
00:47:23,750 --> 00:47:25,250
For my hair's sake.

916
00:47:25,333 --> 00:47:27,083
- [Poppy chuckles]
- Oh, yeah, right.

917
00:47:27,750 --> 00:47:29,458
The famous Poppy poof.

918
00:47:29,542 --> 00:47:30,542
Yeah.

919
00:47:30,917 --> 00:47:33,125
New Orleans is still talking about it.

920
00:47:33,208 --> 00:47:34,208
[jazz music plays]

921
00:47:39,958 --> 00:47:43,792
[man singing] ♪ <i>I feel like funkin' it up</i>
<i>Feel like funkin' it up </i> ♪

922
00:47:44,500 --> 00:47:48,208
♪ <i>I feel like funkin' it up</i>
<i>Feel like funkin' it up </i> ♪

923
00:47:48,708 --> 00:47:52,542
♪ <i>I feel like funkin' it up</i>
<i>Feel like funkin' it up </i> ♪

924
00:47:53,125 --> 00:47:55,333
♪ <i>I feel like funkin' it up</i>
<i>Feel like funkin' it up</i>… ♪

925
00:47:55,417 --> 00:47:58,542
Okay, Napa was fun last year,
but this is next level.

926
00:47:58,625 --> 00:48:01,375
Julian gave me a list of restaurants
we have to go to.

927
00:48:01,458 --> 00:48:04,500
Look at you with the itinerary.
How very un-Poppy.

928
00:48:04,583 --> 00:48:08,583
No, it is not an itinerary.
We can do them in any order that we like.

929
00:48:08,667 --> 00:48:10,750
He had a po'boy
that made him believe in God.

930
00:48:10,833 --> 00:48:13,000
Well, dating a chef
has its perks, I guess.

931
00:48:13,083 --> 00:48:13,958
[Poppy] Hm.

932
00:48:14,042 --> 00:48:17,542
- I'm happy he was okay with you coming.
- Summer trips are non-negotiable.

933
00:48:17,625 --> 00:48:18,792
Cheers to that.

934
00:48:19,333 --> 00:48:23,667
See, I am so happy that Grad-School Alex
didn't kill off Vacation Alex.

935
00:48:23,750 --> 00:48:26,750
Are you kidding me?
Vacation Alex is alive and well.

936
00:48:26,833 --> 00:48:27,833
Thank you.

937
00:48:31,792 --> 00:48:33,792
[jazz music continues in background]

938
00:48:49,167 --> 00:48:51,250
- [jazz music continues]
- [laughing]

939
00:48:54,708 --> 00:48:56,083
Good.

940
00:48:56,167 --> 00:48:57,625
Oh, cheers! [Laughs]

941
00:48:58,208 --> 00:48:59,833
Mm… Mm!

942
00:48:59,917 --> 00:49:01,417
Oh my God.

943
00:49:01,500 --> 00:49:03,708
[Alex] Yup. That is so good.

944
00:49:03,792 --> 00:49:06,208
Maybe we should have done
the beignets and coffee

945
00:49:06,292 --> 00:49:07,375
before the Hurricanes.

946
00:49:07,458 --> 00:49:09,625
- No, I think we did it perfectly.
- Okay.

947
00:49:09,708 --> 00:49:10,708
[jazz music ends]

948
00:49:11,125 --> 00:49:14,583
[server] Beignets on the house
for the lovebirds. Enjoy your honeymoon.

949
00:49:14,667 --> 00:49:16,042
[wife] Thank you! [Laughs]

950
00:49:16,125 --> 00:49:17,625
[Poppy clears her throat]

951
00:49:23,792 --> 00:49:26,125
No. No. [Chuckles]

952
00:49:27,417 --> 00:49:28,417
Hey.

953
00:49:29,875 --> 00:49:33,000
Hey, what a coincidence!

954
00:49:33,083 --> 00:49:35,042
We just got hitched too!

955
00:49:35,125 --> 00:49:37,750
- So sweet.
- Congratulations, you two.

956
00:49:37,833 --> 00:49:40,154
["Hello Hello Hello (Polo & Pan Remix)"
by Remi Wolf plays]

957
00:49:45,667 --> 00:49:47,417
♪ <i>Answers in the room</i>… ♪

958
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:51,958
Drinks and chips are on us, y'all.
Enjoy your honeymoon.

959
00:49:52,042 --> 00:49:54,875
- Oh my God! Thank you!
- Thank you so much.

960
00:49:54,958 --> 00:49:58,500
♪ <i>Hello? How's my little lady</i>
<i>In the New York snow? </i> ♪

961
00:49:58,583 --> 00:50:01,042
♪ <i>Yeah, he says</i>
<i>"I love you, I love you loads" </i> ♪

962
00:50:01,125 --> 00:50:04,667
♪ <i>We got a certified gambler</i>
<i>Messin' with me </i> ♪

963
00:50:06,083 --> 00:50:07,417
[Poppy gasps]

964
00:50:08,083 --> 00:50:09,708
♪ <i>So why she be callin'…? </i> ♪

965
00:50:09,792 --> 00:50:11,708
We just got married!

966
00:50:12,333 --> 00:50:14,042
♪ <i>Hello, hello, hello </i> ♪

967
00:50:14,125 --> 00:50:16,708
♪ <i>How's my little lady</i>
<i>Playin' rock and roll? </i> ♪

968
00:50:16,792 --> 00:50:19,458
♪ <i>Or maybe these days</i>
<i>You like pop and soul </i> ♪

969
00:50:19,542 --> 00:50:22,875
♪ <i>He's a certified gambler</i>
<i>Messin' with me </i> ♪

970
00:50:27,292 --> 00:50:28,542
♪ <i>Hey, hey, hey! </i> ♪

971
00:50:28,625 --> 00:50:30,785
- [mellow background music plays]
- What can I get y'all?

972
00:50:30,833 --> 00:50:33,250
- Gin and tonic, please.
- No, sir.

973
00:50:33,333 --> 00:50:37,583
We will have two Sazeracs
because staying on theme matters.

974
00:50:37,667 --> 00:50:40,583
Right. Theme matters.

975
00:50:40,667 --> 00:50:43,500
- Yeah.
- Are those our fellow newlyweds?

976
00:50:43,583 --> 00:50:47,875
Oh my God. Of course.
Wait, sweetie. Look who it is.

977
00:50:47,958 --> 00:50:50,667
Oh, yeah. It's our beignet buddies.

978
00:50:51,167 --> 00:50:53,375
I hardly recognized you
in that cute little wig.

979
00:50:53,458 --> 00:50:55,000
I'm Stacy Pagano. This is Bob.

980
00:50:55,083 --> 00:50:56,958
Gladys Vivant.

981
00:50:57,042 --> 00:51:00,083
And this is my husband… Keith.

982
00:51:00,583 --> 00:51:02,333
So how did he propose?

983
00:51:02,833 --> 00:51:07,083
Uh, Keith took me to Paris.

984
00:51:07,167 --> 00:51:11,042
He said that it was a work trip.
Cheeky monkey.

985
00:51:11,125 --> 00:51:17,625
Uh, and then he got down on one knee,
and the rest is a blur.

986
00:51:17,708 --> 00:51:20,167
Work in Paris. What do you do, Keith?

987
00:51:20,667 --> 00:51:23,083
[clears throat] I, uh…

988
00:51:23,167 --> 00:51:24,458
I work in government.

989
00:51:25,333 --> 00:51:28,417
You don't have to be shy, baby.
We can trust them.

990
00:51:30,458 --> 00:51:31,875
He's CIA.

991
00:51:32,375 --> 00:51:35,167
Wow. What's that like?

992
00:51:36,500 --> 00:51:39,458
Oh, it's… a lot of coups.

993
00:51:39,542 --> 00:51:41,583
- You know, assassinations.
- [sets down drinks]

994
00:51:44,750 --> 00:51:46,583
Just boring stuff, really.

995
00:51:47,583 --> 00:51:48,958
But the benefits are great.

996
00:51:49,042 --> 00:51:50,042
Goodness.

997
00:51:50,833 --> 00:51:52,250
Is it dangerous?

998
00:51:52,333 --> 00:51:56,292
Well, it's nothing compared
to Gladys's work on the oil rigs.

999
00:51:56,375 --> 00:51:57,375
[Poppy chokes]

1000
00:51:59,542 --> 00:52:03,000
- [Poppy coughs]
- Wow. You two are something else.

1001
00:52:03,083 --> 00:52:04,083
How'd you meet?

